South African Equities: Anglo, Gold Reef, Hulamin, Kumba, Sasol

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-02-11T16:03:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-11/south-african-equities-anglo-gold-reef-hulamin-kumba-sasol.html
  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index snapped four days of declines, rising 544.85, or 1.7
percent, to 32,954.33 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg,
taking its gain to 2.6 percent so far this year.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 11 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, jumped 11.21 rand, or 2.9 percent, to 393 rand, taking
the year’s increase to 15 percent.  De Beers , a unit of Anglo
American, plans to produce diamonds at a rate of about 40
million carats annually by the end of 2012, acting Chief
Executive Officer Bruce Cleaver said on a conference call today.    Gold Reef Resorts Ltd . (GDF SJ), a casino and gaming
company, climbed 1.15 rand, or 6.9 percent, to 17.95 rand,
leaving it unchanged in the week. The Competition Tribunal of
South Africa said it will today release its decision on whether
the gaming company may merge with Tsogo Sun Holdings.    Hulamin Ltd . (HLM SJ), an aluminum processor, dropped to
the lowest level since Nov. 2, falling 22 cents, or 2.6 percent,
to 8.18 rand. Hulamin said today that earnings for the year
ended December are expected to be as much as 78 million rand
($10.7 million), compared with the previous estimate of a
maximum 69 million-rand loss.    Kumba Iron Ore Ltd . (KIO SJ), a unit of Anglo American,
advanced 8.50 rand, or 1.9 percent, to 469 rand, the highest
since Jan. 19, extending its gain this year to 10.5 percent. The
Department of Mineral Resources agreed to delay the award of a
partial mining right over its Sishen mine to Imperial Crown
Trading until Kumba’s legal challenge to an initial prospecting
right is heard,  Business Day  newspaper said, citing Chief
Financial Officer Vincent Uren.    Sasol Ltd . (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, jumped 12.69 rand, or 3.4 percent, to 382.50
rand, the highest since September 2008. That extended its
increase this year to 10.5 percent. Sasol had its credit outlook
revised by  Standard & Poor’s  to “stable” from “negative.”    Trencor Ltd . (TRE SJ), an investment company, rose for the
first day in seven, gaining 1.20 rand, or 3.5 percent, to 36
rand, the highest since Feb. 3. The company said it expects to
report earnings excluding one-time items of between 3.60 rand
and 3.80 rand a share for the year through December, compared
with earnings of 2.035 rand a share a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
